Draghi: APP is open ended and is not going to stop suddenly
Draghi: Euro area is later in the business cycle compared to US; that justifies a different monetary policy stance
Constâncio: NPL targets are important but manageable. Banks need to comply or explain in supervisory dialogue.
Draghi: Large majority of Governing Council members preferred to have the APP open ended
Draghi: Improving labour market and positive survey indicators indicate that the output gap is shrinking
Draghi: Monetary policy has contributed to the creation of more than seven million jobs in four years
Draghi: The stock of purchased assets has become more and more important
Introductory statement Mario Draghi to the press conference https://t.co/rXICgPiUZz
Draghi: All countries would benefit from intensifying efforts towards achieving a more growth-friendly composition of public finances
Draghi: Other policy areas must contribute decisively to strengthening the longer-term growth potential and reducing vulnerabilities
Draghi: Net asset purchases, sizeable stock of acquired assets and reinvestments, and forward guidance on rates provide monetary support
Draghi: Domestic price pressures still muted. Economic outlook and path of inflation still conditional on continued monetary policy support.
Draghi: Recalibration of asset purchases reflects growing confidence in gradual convergence of inflation rates towards our inflation aim
Draghi: Fixed rate tender procedures with full allotment to be applied in MROs and 3-month LTROs for as long as necessary
Draghi: This will contribute both to favourable liquidity conditions and to an appropriate monetary policy stance
Draghi: If outlook becomes less favourable, we stand ready to increase the APP in terms of size and/or duration
Draghi: …and in any case until the Governing Council sees a sustained adjustment in the path of inflation consistent with inflation aim
Draghi: From Jan 2018 net asset purchases intended to continue at monthly pace of €30 bln until end of Sept 2018, or beyond, if necessary…
Draghi: We expect rates to remain at their present levels for extended period of time, and well past the horizon of our net asset purchases
